1. Objectives and Goals

The primary objective of this assignment is to illustrate that you understand the final steps of bulk-RNAseq data processing as it pertains to data clean up, modeling and differential gene expression analysis. By the end of this lecture and assignment you should be able to:

  • use DESeq2 for count normalization and differential gene expression analysis
  • use prcomp to perform PCA
  • generate and interpret PCA plots in order to identify potential covariates or batch effects
  • generate and interpret QC plots for differential expression analysis
  • perform DE analysis between different biological groups


knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

3. Bulk RNA-seq Statitical Analysis

Purpose: To understand and be able read in your data to generate a counts matrix with approriately linked metadata for differential gene expression analysis. Additionally, this will help you walk through how to think through and filter out data, why we use negative binomial distributions to model RNA seq counts data, and how to execute the statistics in order to perform differential gene expression analysis.

3.2 Filtering and normalization

  1. Perform the following tasks as they pertain to pre-filtering data, generating a DESeq2 data object, normalization, and accessing normalized counts
  1. Filter out any genes where the raw counts across all samples is less than 10 and generate a new counts matrix
  2. Create a DESeq2 object using biological_groups as the outcome to test and place your filtered data, metadata, and design as a deseq2 data object
  3. Apply the normalization
  4. Extract the normalized counts and store them in a variable
  5. Save your normalized counts file as a csv file with whatever file name of your choice for later use
# TO DO

#A
keep <- rowSums(geneCounts) >= 10
filteredGeneCounts <- geneCounts[keep, ]

#B
deData <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = filteredGeneCounts, colData = metadata, design = ~ biological_groups)
## Warning in DESeqDataSet(se, design = design, ignoreRank): some variables in

3.3 PCA

  1. Perform the following tasks as they pertain to PCA and data exploration to identify covariates
  1. Run PCA on your normalized counts and store the resulting data object into a variable
  2. Merge your PCs dataframe with your metadata dataframe
  3. Generate the following 4 plots:
  • PC1 vs PC2 colored by biological groups
  • PC2 vs PC3 colored by biological groups
  • PC1 vs PC2 colored by replicate
  • PC2 vs PC3 colored by replicate
# TO DO

#A
pcs <- prcomp(t(normCountsDf), scale. = TRUE)

#B
metadata <- cbind(pcs$x, metadata)

#C
##Plot Generation
ggplot(metadata, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = biological_groups)) + geom_point()

ggplot(metadata, aes(x = PC2, y = PC3, color = biological_groups)) + geom_point()

ggplot(metadata, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = replicate)) + geom_point()

ggplot(metadata, aes(x = PC2, y = PC3, color = replicate)) + geom_point()

Critical Thinking Exercises

Question 1

How many total genes were in your original input counts matrix before filtering? How many were remaining after you filtered?

geneCounts contained 25239 genes, but the new filtered matrix has 14247 genes.

Question 2

TRUE or FALSE. DESeq2 can be used to compare relative expression levels across different genes within the same sample. Defend or refute your answer.

FALSE. DESeq2 cannot be used for witihin sample comparisons because normalization does not account for gene length and other within sample biases. Another normalization method would need to be utilized.


Question 3

Why is it important to run PCA on your normalized pre-filtered gene counts data matrix?

It’s important to run PCA on your normalized, pre-filtered gene counts data matrix because comparing prior to normalization will re-introduce the potential biases we corrected for into the PCA analyses, and if we perform after filtering, that effect may be minimized and nonvisible during the PCA comparison.


Question 4

When running differential expression analysis why is it important to look at the distribution of unadjusted p-values? What can you say about the histogram of unadjusted p-value for (a) the DE results of 30min_N4_PRN-694 relative to 30min_N4, and (b) the DE results of 30min_N4 relative to 30min_unstim. Does this seem to make sense based on the PCA? Why or why not?

It is important to look at the distribution of unadjusted p-values for (a) to see the relative frequency of genes significantly upregulated or downregulated with the addition of PRN-694 versus no inhibitor with stimulation, as well as compare (b) to understand the effect that stimulation alone has on the distribution of signicantly upregulated/downregulated genes. This helps us understand the potential impact the inihibtor in the context of stimulation that may/may not be explainable by stimulation alone. This is potentially explained in the PCA analysis, colored by biological group, in PC2 vs PC3, but not by PC1 vs PC2. In PC2 vs PC3, you can see a graded effect of each of the replicates shifting towards PC2 or PC3 in a linear fashion.


Question 5

What are the top 5 down-regulated genes in the 30min_N4_PRN-694 group relative to the 30min_N4 gruop that meet an adjusted p-value < 0.05? By top 5 down-regulated I mean the top 5 most negative fold change differences.

Cd19, H2-Aa, Hck, Hpgd, C1qc.

STEP8: Graphing and Summary

Write code to generate a volcano plot of all genes. Add a vertical line at x = 1 and x = -1 and a horizonal line that is equivalent to an adjusted p-value of 0.05. How many genes are upregulated at a log2(fold change) of greater than 1 and have an adjusted pvalue of less than 0.05? How many genes are downregulated at a log2(fold change) of less than than -1 and have an adjusted pvalue of less than 0.05?

# TO DO

myResults3$negLog10FDR <- (-1) * log10(myResults3$padj)
myResults3$gene <- rownames(myResults3)
class(myResults3)
## [1] "DESeqResults"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "DESeq2"
myResults3df <- as.data.frame(myResults3)
ggplot(myResults3df, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = negLog10FDR)) +
      geom_point() +
      geom_vline(xintercept=c(-1, 1), col="red") +
      geom_hline(yintercept= (-1) * log10(0.05), col="red") +
      geom_text_repel(data=subset(myResults3df, padj < 0.05), aes(label = gene)) +
      xlim(-11, 11)
## Warning: Removed 6358 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: ggrepel: 263 unlabeled data points (too many overlaps). Consider
## increasing max.overlaps

#Genes upregulated at >1 and padj <0.05 = 103
myResults3dfUp <- myResults3df[which(myResults3df$log2FoldChange > 1), ]
myResults3dfUpSig <- myResults3dfUp[which(myResults3dfUp$padj < 0.05), ]
dim(myResults3dfUpSig)
## [1] 103   8
#Genes downregulated at <1 and padj <0.05 = 175
myResults3dfDown <- myResults3df[which(myResults3df$log2FoldChange < 1), ]
myResults3dfDownSig <- myResults3dfDown[which(myResults3dfDown$padj < 0.05), ]
dim(myResults3dfDownSig)
## [1] 175   8
